<i>-ingas</i>.","English: from Middle English <i>Inge</i>, itself either from the Old Norse female personal name <i>Inga</i> (a pet form of such names as <i>Ingi(v)aldr</i>), or from the Scandinavian male personal name <i>Inge</i> (a pet form of such names as <i>Ingiríthr</i>), or the Anglo-Saxon form of such a name, <i>Inga</i>. Unless there are other indications of gender, the two sources cannot be distinguished.","German: probably from the ancient Germanic female personal name <i>Inga</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Ing","meanings":["English (Buckinghamshire and Middlesex): variant of   Inge  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): nickname from Yiddish <i>ing</i> ‘young’.","Chinese: alternative Cantonese form of the surnames 應, 嬴, and 英, see   Ying   1-3."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Inge was born in 1246, in Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Inge, was 28 and his mother, Mrs William Inge, was 27. He had at least 2 sons. He died in 1303, in his hometo